## 4. The Architecture

### 4.1 Three Layers, Three Jobs

| Layer | What It Does | Who Writes It |
|---|---|---|
| Object | Carries the content — the Journey, the Moment, the Keeper, the Domain. | Kip · Platform |
| Present | Names the form the object takes in this context. | Rendr · Owner approves |
| Treatment | Governs how that form feels — motion, density, spatial ratios, presence. | Rendr · Owner approves |

### 4.2 The Present Definition — Data

A Present is a named configuration. It lives in the database or domain JSON alongside the Treatment. It is the instruction — not code.

```json
{
  "present": "cover",
  "treatment": "cinematic",
  "subject": { "type": "journey", "id": "..." }
}
```

Rendr writes this. The owner approves it. The platform renders it. No domain owner writes Present JSON by hand.

### 4.3 The Present Renderer — Theatre.js

This is the critical architectural decision locked in this document.

Presents are not static React components. They are Theatre.js sequences — authored definitions of how values change over time. KeeperPresence is built as a Theatre.js listener from the start.

The Present definition in the database includes a sequence reference. The KeeperPresence component responds to the values Theatre.js is playing. It does not need to know which Present it is — it responds to values.

A Cover sequence is different from a Slide sequence is different from a Media sequence. But they all play through the same React listener. Swap the sequence, the presentation changes. No new React component required.

> *This is the data-driven philosophy carried all the way into motion. JSON is the instruction. The component is an intelligent empty vessel. The sequence is the Present.*

### 4.4 Motion Tier and Theatre.js

| Library | Role in Presents |
|---|---|
| Framer Motion | Ambient transitions at all tiers. Always present. Does not govern Presents. |
| GSAP | Standard Treatment tier. Scroll choreography, directed motion. Not the Present renderer. |
| Theatre.js | The Present renderer. Sequences that govern how a Present unfolds. Cinematic Treatment tier and above. |
| R3F | Immersive Treatment tier. Spatial worlds. Presents in three-dimensional space. |

Theatre.js at this level requires a human creative director in the loop. Sequences are not generated — they are authored. Rendr is the right agent for this. Rendr authors Theatre.js sequences as part of its Treatment output. The human approves. The sequence is stored with the Present definition.

### 4.5 KeeperPresence — Updated Signature

KeeperPresence currently receives `object`, `context`, and `treatment`. The `context` prop is typed as a location — `'chronicle'`, `'feed'`, `'journey'`. That is a location context. It answers where the object is appearing, not how it is presenting.

A `present` field is added alongside `context`. These are not the same thing and must not be collapsed.

```typescript
interface KeeperPresenceProps {
  object: KeeperObject
  present: PresentName         // 'cover' | 'slide' | 'media' | 'journey' | 'moment' | string
  context: RenderContext       // where it is appearing
  treatment: TreatmentJSON     // how it feels
  onSelect?: () => void
}
```

`PresentName` is a string, not a closed enum. The catalog grows as content demands it. The architecture does not require a rebuild when a new Present is named.

