## 7. What Is Locked

These decisions are locked. Do not substitute, reframe, or reopen without a deliberate architectural decision recorded in a Moment.

| Decision | What Is Locked |
|---|---|
| Presents are universal | A Cover is a Cover. Any object can inhabit any Present. Object-specific Present variants are configurations, not new Present types. |
| Three-layer render stack | Object → Present → Treatment. Each layer does one job. They are not collapsed. |
| Present catalog is open | Five names confirmed: Cover, Slide, Media, Journey, Moment. New names emerge from content. No premature naming. |
| Presents are Theatre.js sequences | Not static React components. KeeperPresence is built as a Theatre.js listener from the start. This is not retrofitted later. |
| `present` is a prop on KeeperPresence | Alongside `context` (location) and `treatment` (feeling). `context` and `present` are not the same field. |
| Default sequences ship with the platform | Cursor authors the five default sequences in code. They are exported as Theatre.js JSON and stored as the platform's default Present catalog. Rendr overrides per domain. The platform does not wait for Rendr to ship working Presents. |
| Theatre.js Studio is the human edit surface | The visual editor is Theatre.js's own tool. We do not build a custom sequence editor. We use the one that ships with the library. |
| Rendr authors bespoke sequences | When Rendr is built, it produces domain-specific sequences that override the defaults. Rendr's sequences are always human-approved before they render. |
| Theatre.js installs in three places | Local dev, Vercel (frontend), and Railway (if any sequence rendering runs server-side). SSR compatibility confirmed before installation. Performance targets named first. |

