## 8. Default Sequences — What Cursor Authors

Cursor authors the five default Present sequences before Rendr exists. These are not placeholders — they are disciplined, intentional defaults that work for any domain. Rendr makes them bespoke. The defaults ship with the platform.

### 8.1 Authoring Approach

Cursor writes the sequences as Theatre.js sheet definitions in code. Each sequence is a named sheet with tracks governing the values KeeperPresence listens to. Once written, Theatre.js Studio can open, inspect, and edit them visually. The human does not touch code to adjust timing, easing, or value curves — that is Theatre.js Studio's job.

The authored sequences are exported as Theatre.js project JSON and stored in the platform's default Present catalog — a static file that ships with the codebase. Domain-level overrides (authored by Rendr) are stored in domain JSON and take precedence at runtime.

### 8.2 The Five Default Sequences

| Present | Default Sequence Character |
|---|---|
| **Cover** | Atmosphere expands slowly. Domain identity fades in from opacity 0 over 1.2s. Content arrives after atmosphere is present — not simultaneously. Unhurried. The guest is received, not presented at. |
| **Slide** | Content steps into view. Primary field arrives first. Secondary fields follow at 200ms intervals. Narrative context fades in last. Forward motion — each beat confirms the previous before the next arrives. |
| **Media** | Opens full. No preamble. The media is the experience. Caption arrives quietly after 800ms. Controls are ambient — present on hover, recessive otherwise. Nothing competes with the content. |
| **Journey** | Arc motion. The story has a beginning — the title and forward arrive together. Paths surface sequentially, not simultaneously. The sense of going somewhere. Motion mirrors narrative structure. |
| **Moment** | Full depth, deliberate pace. The Moment title arrives. A breath. Then the narrative. Then context — Journey, Path, date — fades in beneath. The Moment is held, not skimmed. |

### 8.3 What KeeperPresence Listens To

KeeperPresence does not branch on present name. It listens to a set of named values that Theatre.js plays. The sequence determines what those values do. The component responds.

| Value Name | What It Controls |
|---|---|
| `atmosphereOpacity` | Background atmosphere — how present the domain's visual context is |
| `primaryOpacity` | The primary field — title, name, or lead content |
| `secondaryOpacity` | Secondary fields — supporting content, descriptions |
| `contextOpacity` | Ambient context — Journey name, Path, date, provenance |
| `mediaScale` | For Media presents — how the content fills the surface |
| `contentOffsetY` | Vertical entry offset — how far content travels on arrival |
| `captionOpacity` | Captions, whispers, and ambient labels |

This value set is the starting definition. It is not closed. New values are added when a Present sequence requires them. The component must handle unknown values gracefully — ignore what it does not know.

### 8.4 Installation — Where Theatre.js Lives

Theatre.js must be installed and confirmed working in three environments before any Present sequence is authored. Do not author sequences in an environment where Theatre.js is not confirmed.

| Environment | What Installs | Confirmation |
|---|---|---|
| Local dev | `@theatre/core` + `@theatre/studio`. Studio is dev-only — never ships to production. | Theatre.js Studio opens in browser. A test sheet animates a value. Studio exports JSON without error. |
| Vercel (production) | `@theatre/core` only. Studio is excluded from the production bundle via build config. | Deployed build plays a sequence from stored JSON. No Studio UI present. No SSR errors. Bundle size confirmed within budget. |
| Railway (API/backend) | Only if sequence rendering or JSON storage runs server-side. Likely `@theatre/core` only, or not needed at all if sequences are purely frontend. | Confirm whether Railway needs Theatre.js at all before installing. Do not install speculatively. |

> **SSR is the critical risk.** Theatre.js `@theatre/core` has known SSR considerations with Next.js. Cursor must confirm the correct client-only boundary pattern before writing any sequence code. The standard pattern is `dynamic import with ssr: false`. Confirm this works with the current Vercel deployment before proceeding.

### 8.5 Build Sequence for This Prompt

| Step | What Cursor Does |
|---|---|
| 1 — Diagnostic | Read the current `package.json` files across `apps/web` and `apps/api`. Report whether `@theatre/core` or `@theatre/studio` appear anywhere. Report the current Next.js version and SSR configuration. |
| 2 — SSR confirmation | Confirm the correct dynamic import pattern for Theatre.js with this Next.js version. Write a minimal test component that imports `@theatre/core` with `ssr: false`. Confirm it renders without error in a Vercel preview deploy. |
| 3 — Install | Install `@theatre/core` in `apps/web`. Install `@theatre/studio` as a dev dependency in `apps/web`. Exclude Studio from the production bundle via `next.config.js`. Do not install in `apps/api` unless Step 1 confirms it is needed. |
| 4 — Default catalog | Create `apps/web/src/v0/presents/defaultSequences.ts` — the five default Present sheets as Theatre.js project JSON. One sheet per Present. Named values matching the value set in Section 8.3. |
| 5 — KeeperPresence update | Add `present: PresentName` to `KeeperPresenceProps`. Wire Theatre.js listener to the named values. Component responds to values — does not branch on present name. |
| 6 — Confirm in browser | A Journey object inhabiting a Cover Present animates correctly using the default sequence. Theatre.js Studio opens in dev and shows the Cover sheet with editable tracks. |

